<figure class='article-image'><img alt="Twiiter" class="microcontent" data-fragment="lead-image" data-image="http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE1LzA3LzMxLzI5L3R3aWl0ZXIuZGVhMGUuanBnCnAJdGh1bWIJOTUweDUzNCMKZQlqcGc/6430348d/50c/twiiter.jpg" data-micro="1" data-url="null" src="http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE1LzA3LzMxLzI5L3R3aWl0ZXIuZGVhMGUuanBnCnAJdGh1bWIJOTUweDUzNCMKZQlqcGc/6430348d/50c/twiiter.jpg" /><div class="image-credit">Image: <a href="https://twitter.com/queenfeminist/status/624619788262715392" target="_blank">TWITTER</a></div></figure>

<div class="article-info"><a class="byline" href="/people/lindsey-robertson/"><img alt="Lindsey-9855_1200_web" class="author_image" src="http://rack.2.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE1LzA0LzIxLzNjL0xpbmRzZXk5ODU1LjQ5Njk0LmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTkweDkwIwplCWpwZw/d6d605f9/9ff/Lindsey-9855_1200_web.jpg" /><div class="author_and_date"><span class="author_name">By Lindsey Robertson</span><time datetime="Fri, 31 Jul 2015 20:13:37 +0000">2015-07-31 20:13:37 UTC</time></div></a></div>

</header>
<section class='article-content'>

<p>Who wears short-shorts? Not JC Penney employees, apparently.</p>
<p><a href="https://twitter.com/queenfeminist" target="_blank">Sylva Stoel</a>, a 17-year-old sales associate at JC Penney in Sioux Falls, North Dakota, was sent home for wearing shorts that were apparently not work-appropriate. The ironic part? She purchased the shorts at JC Penney in the store's "career department."</p>
<div class="see-also"><p>See also: <a href="http://mashable.com/2015/05/30/sexist-graduation-dress-code-letter/" data-crackerjax="#post-slider">High school student angered by sexist graduation dress code letter</a></p></div>
<figure class="image"><p><img data-credit-link="https://twitter.com/queenfeminist/status/624619788262715392" data-credit-name="Twitter " data-credit-provider="" data-caption="" title="JC Penney" src="http://rack.0.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDE1LzA3LzMxLzZkL0pDUGVubmV5LmQ2MDVjLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTEyMDB4OTYwMD4/5b18ec3f/96f/JC-Penney.jpg" alt="JC Penney" class="" data-width="449"></p>
<div class="image-credit"><p>Image: <a href="https://twitter.com/queenfeminist/status/624619788262715392" target="_blank">Twitter </a></p></div></figure><p>Stoel tweeted about the incident, saying she was expected to go home and change out of the shorts, despite the fact that the store evidently deemed them work-appropriate for customers.  </p>
<blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-cards="hidden" lang="en">
<p lang="en" dir="ltr">Boss sent me home for wearing "too revealing" shorts that I bought from the store I work at in the career section. <a href="http://t.co/vrAnN4beC2" target="_blank">pic.twitter.com/vrAnN4beC2</a></p>
<p>— Sylva (@queenfeminist) <a href="https://twitter.com/queenfeminist/status/624618091935236096" target="_blank">July 24, 2015</a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Stoel then stated she wasn't going to return following the incident.  </p>
<blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-conversation="none" lang="en">
<p lang="en" dir="ltr">He asked how long it'd take for me to go home &amp; change. I said "idk probably the whole day" I'm not coming back</p>
<p>— Sylva (@queenfeminist) <a href="https://twitter.com/queenfeminist/status/624619788262715392" target="_blank">July 24, 2015</a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Although she was told that shorts were against employee dress code, Stoel said she was never alerted of that fact prior. </p>
<p>"They never said 'no shorts' at orientation," she told <a href="http://www.people.com/article/jcpenney-employee-fired-shorts" target="_blank">People</a>. "I never even got a handbook or anything. The manager was asked and she said no tank tops, spaghetti straps, absolutely no denim and no T-shirts. And when asked for clarification she said, nothing that you're falling out of. So I thought, 'I'm not falling out of these shorts.'" </p>
<p>Stoel rage-tweeted a considerable amount, noting she felt the supposed rule was arbitrary and anti-feminist. </p>
<blockquote class="twitter-tweet" lang="en">
<p lang="en" dir="ltr">Good dress code rules: no gang attire, no explicit imagery, no pajamas...<br>Bad dress code rules: no female shoulders, legs, bra straps...</p>
<p>— Sylva (@queenfeminist) <a href="https://twitter.com/queenfeminist/status/626069139501658112" target="_blank">July 28, 2015</a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>JC Penney told Mashable in an email, however, that the dress code isn't discriminatory at all:</p>
<blockquote><p>JCPenney's dress code policy for store associates prohibits wearing shorts of any length.  New store associates who join the company are given a copy of the dress code policy and are required to sign an acknowledgment form as part of their on boarding process . This policy applies to both male and female associates at every store.</p></blockquote>
<p>Regardless of whether or not JC Penney was in the wrong on this one, Stoel is currently looking for <a href="http://www.today.com/style/j-c-penney-employee-sent-home-wearing-shorts-she-bought-t35181" target="_blank">employment elsewhere</a>.</p>
